1. By “perfection,” I do not mean to reduce God to an impersonal ideal, a psychological archetype, or a symbolic highest value, as Carl Jung or Jordan Peterson seem to do. I mean the Holy and Righteous living God who creates, commands, judges, and acts in history. God is perfect, yes, but he is also much more.
2. By “corrupted to the core,” I am referring to the doctrine of Original Sin. This doctrine holds that sin is not merely a series of bad actions, but a condition inherited from Adam that affects the whole human person: mind, will, and desires (Rom 5:12-19). Christians have disagreed about the extent of this corruption, a debate reflected across Augustine, Aquinas, Luther, and many others. In this paper, I follow the basic Pauline claim that sin is universal, inherited, and inescapable by human effort. This will be the topic of a future essay.
3. Christian theology overlaps with non-biblical schools of thought, especially Greek metaphysics. For example, concepts such as essence, being, and perfection overlap with those of Plato and Aristotle, though they clearly reach different conclusions.
4. Romans 8:7; James 4:4; 1 John 3:4; James 2:9-11; Romans 3:23; 1 John 1:8; James 4:17; Galatians 5:19-21; Romans 1:25; Matthew 6:21, 24; Deuteronomy 6:5; Isaiah 1:2; 1 Samuel 15:23; Daniel 9:5
5. Lexical usage of hamartia, chata, anomia, parabasis, and pesha as reflected across the Old and New Testaments.
6. Though Luther does not consistently use the phrase verbatim, he repeatedly describes sin as the human heart turned inward upon itself, seeking itself in all things; later theologians summarize this idea as incurvatus in se. See Luther, Lectures on Romans (LW 25) and The Bondage of the Will.
7. Buddhism diagnoses suffering (dukkha) as arising from attachment and self-clinging (taṇhā, upādāna), particularly the fixation on “I” and “mine” (cf. SN 22.59). While Christianity and Buddhism radically disagree on God, creation, and salvation, both recognize that inward self-centeredness produces suffering. The similarity will be explored in a future essay, but it’s worth pointing out here.
8. Scripture repeatedly warns that religious devotion can be self-seeking rather than faithful, condemning prayer, obedience, and service when they are performed for recognition, justification, or reward rather than love of God and neighbor (Matt 6:1-5; Matt 23:5-7; Luke 18:9-14; Luke 15:29; Isa 29:13; Matt 15:8). Scripture also rebukes any attempt to stand before God on such devotion, insisting that righteousness comes apart from works of the Law and that to rely on obedience rather than Christ attempts to nullify the cross (Rom 3:21-28; Gal 2:21; Phil 3:9; Heb 10:14).

